    "title": "A HYBRID TRAINED DEEP LEARNING APPROACH FOR SOLVING PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS",
    "abstract": "Abstract. Artificial neural network-based methods for solving partial differential equations have garnered significant attention over the past decade due to their exceptional success. Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) use physical constraints during the training process to enhance both accuracy and generalizability of the solution. This method faces difficulties in achieving a global minimum and ensuring global optimization, and often fails to surpass certain levels of accuracy due to getting stuck in local minima. Extreme learning machines (ELMs) have shown to be more advantageous in addressing these challenges, demonstrating superior accuracy compared to existing methods. Also, due to their simple structure and training procedure, the computational burden of parameter optimization is significantly reduced. However, the ELMs also have some drawbacks. Because of the randomized basis functions, the ELMs may yield suboptimal approximation performance for solving some PDEs. The objective of this study is to develop a hybrid model, hybrid trained physics informed neural network (HT-PINN), that combines the strengths of the PINNs and ELMs. With this approach, after some gradient descent updates performed with the PINN, an ELM update will be carried out for training the output weights. This approach ensures that the basis functions are also learned in each ELM cycle. It has been shown that this method yields better results than both ELM and PINN.",
    "venue": "International Conference on Modern Problems of Mathematics, Mechanics and their Applications",
    "year": 2024,
